07056nam a22008295i 9780822386681DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20052005ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)1229161883  a97808223866817 a10.1515/97808223866812doi  a(DE-B1597)553167  a(OCoLC)1171361941  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aBR162.3b.C85 2005 7aREL0150002bisacsh1 aRousseau, Philip, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Cultural Turn in Late Ancient Studies :bGender, Asceticism, and Historiography /cPhilip Rousseau; ed. by Dale B. Martin, Patricia Cox Miller. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2005] 4c©2005  a1 online resource (376 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tcontents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tgender -- tThe Lady Appears: Materializations of ‘‘Woman’’ in Early Monastic Literature -- tNo Friendly Letters: Augustine’s Correspondence with Women -- tOn Mary’s Voice: Gendered Words in Syriac Marian Tradition -- tIs There a Harlot in This Text?: Hagiography and the Grotesque -- tMacrina’s Tattoo -- tasceticism -- tRereading the Jovinianist Controversy: Asceticism and Clerical Authority in Late Ancient Christianity -- tThe Dark Side of Landscape: Ideology and Power in the Christian Myth of the Desert -- tMonks and Other Animals -- thistoriography -- tArchives in the Fiction: Rabbinic Historiography and Church History -- tHow to Read Heresiology -- tAscetic Practice and the Genealogy of Heresy: Problems in Modern Scholarship and Ancient Textual Representation -- tHistory, Fiction, and Figuralism in Book 8 of Augustine’s Confessions -- tHellenism and Historiography: Gregory of Nazianzus and Julian in Dialogue -- tKnowing Theodoret: Text and Self -- tDamasus and the Invention of Early Christian Rome -- tBibliography -- tContributors -- tIndex of Modern Authors -- tIndex of Citations to Ancient Authors and Scriptures0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe essays in this provocative collection exemplify the innovations that have characterized the relatively new field of late ancient studies. Focused on civilizations clustered mainly around the Mediterranean and covering the period between roughly 100 and 700 CE, scholars in this field have brought history and cultural studies to bear on theology and religious studies. They have adopted the methods of the social sciences and humanities—particularly those of sociology, cultural anthropology, and literary criticism. By emphasizing cultural and social history and considerations of gender and sexuality, scholars of late antiquity have revealed the late ancient world as far more varied than had previously been imagined.The contributors investigate three key concerns of late ancient studies: gender, asceticism, and historiography. They consider Macrina’s scar, Mary’s voice, and the harlot’s body as well as Augustine, Jovinian, Gregory of Nazianzus, Julian, and Ephrem the Syrian. Whether examining how animal bodies figured as a means for understanding human passion and sexuality in the monastic communities of Egypt and Palestine or meditating on the almost modern epistemological crisis faced by Theodoret in attempting to overcome the barriers between the self and the wider world, these essays highlight emerging theoretical and critical developments in the field.Contributors. Daniel Boyarin, David Brakke, Virginia Burrus, Averil Cameron, Susanna Elm, James E. Goehring, Susan Ashbrook Harvey, David G. Hunter, Blake Leyerle, Dale B. Martin, Patricia Cox Miller, Philip Rousseau, Teresa M. Shaw, Maureen A. Tilley, Dennis E. Trout, Mark Vessey  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aAsceticism. 0aChristianityxInfluen